Abstract = {{This paper provides an assessment of the ability of different
   international relations theories to grasp modern uses of international
   digital disinformation. More specifically, the paper argues that E. H.
   Carr's notion of propaganda, John J. Mearsheimer's typology of lies and
   Joseph Nye's conceptualisation of public diplomacy all offer useful
   theoretical lenses through which we can advance our understanding of
   international digital disinformation. Their added value is demonstrated
   by applying these three theoretical perspectives to three `prototype
   cases' of modern international digital disinformation. The paper
   concludes that the three theoretical perspectives make new aspects of
   international digital disinformation intelligible, including the
   underlying motives for using digital disinformation. However, there
   still remains a space for a more detailed theoretical account of digital
