Pages = {{1301-1326}},
Month = {{MAY}},
Abstract = {{The scale, volume, and distribution speed of disinformation raise
   concerns in governments, businesses, and citizens. To respond
   effectively to this problem, we first need to disambiguate, understand,
   and clearly define the phenomenon. Our online information landscape is
   characterized by a variety of different types of false information.
   There is no commonly agreed typology framework, specific categorization
   criteria, and explicit definitions as a basis to assist the further
   investigation of the area. Our work is focused on filling this need. Our
   contribution is twofold. First, we collect the various implicit and
   explicit disinformation typologies proposed by scholars. We consolidate
   the findings following certain design principles to articulate an
   all-inclusive disinformation typology. Second, we propose three
   independent dimensions with controlled values per dimension as
   categorization criteria for all types of disinformation. The taxonomy
   can promote and support further multidisciplinary research to analyze
