Abstract = {{Our paper focuses on one of the newest challenges for the education
   system: the design and implementation of proper interventions as a
   response to the proliferation of fake news and online disinformation in
   the digital ecosystem.
   The European Commission included media and information literacy (MIL)
   among the most sought-after solutions in dealing with online
   communication disorders. Defined as the capacity of the audience to use
   and interact with the media, and to assess its contents in a critical
   manner, MIL enables citizens to understand the new information
   environment of the digital age and to take more informed decisions,
   reducing their vulnerability to disinformation. Raising awareness and
   improving societal resilience is one of the four pillars of the EU's
   Action Plan to counter disinformation in Europe, and one main ways to
   reach this objective is through MIL interventions for all ages.
   Reflecting on the increased relevance of the topic, we provide insights
   on the extant research on MIL interventions for building resilience to
   fake news. In the empirical section, we turn to recent surveys, reports
   and analyses from reputable sources, such as the European Commission and
   other relevant organizations that provide insightful information on the
   digital behaviour of the citizens. By means of secondary data analysis,
   we look at relevant survey data tackling the fake news phenomenon. We
   aim at understanding what the public perceptions on fake news prevalence
   are, and what the current levels of trust in traditional and online
   media are. Furthermore, we pay particular attention to the digital
   behavior of the young generations, and we explore associated
   vulnerabilities to disinformation. Lastly, we seek to identify best
   practices in designing MIL interventions to correct the digital
