Volume = {{97}},
Number = {{3}},
Pages = {{841+}},
Month = {{MAY}},
Abstract = {{This article explores the transformative role of practices of countering
   digital disinformation in European Union diplomacy. It argues that an
   overlooked dimension of the change brought by the rise of digital
   disinformation is located in the emergence of everyday countering
   practices. Efforts to counter disinformation have led to the recruitment
   of new actors with different dispositions and skill sets than those of
   traditional diplomats and state officials in diplomatic organizations
   such as the European External Action Service. Focusing on the countering
   efforts by the East StratCom Task Force, a unit introduced in 2015, the
   article argues that the composition of actors, the task force's
   practices and the reorientation in audience perception it reflected,
   contributed significantly to institutional transformation. Drawing on 23
   interviews with key actors and building on recent advancements in
   international practice theory, the article shows how change and
   transformation can be studied in practices that have resulted from
   digitalization in international politics. The article thus contributes
   to an increased understanding of the digitalization of diplomacy in
   which new practices can emerge from both deliberate reflection and
   experimentation.}},
