Abstract = {{Action against disinformation has become more important than ever in the
   context of the Covid-19 pandemic. This is due to the synchronous global
   scale of the problem and its potentially deadlier consequences as the
   public seeks out guidance regarding what they might do to lower the risk
   of infection. This article investigates the impact of the Covid-19
   crisis on the regulation of social media platforms as it is mediated by
   the legacy of previous responses to disinformation. It shows that the
