   reached a wider audience than nonemotional tweets in the first
   large-scale attempt to interfere in the US presidential election in
   2016. We contrasted the dimensional and discrete theories of emotion by
   comparing tweets' virality as a function of their valence or discrete
   emotional content. While both perspectives were supported by the
   popularity of positive and joyful tweets, the unpopularity of negative
   and fearful tweets uniquely supported the discrete view. The robustness
