Abstract = {{The main objective of the research outlined in this paper is to
   understand how higher education students who are attending a Media and
   Communication bachelor's degree perceive some aspects related to fake
   news and online disinformation. To conduct this case study, information
   was collected using an online questionnaire and a focus group. In this
   paper, we present the results collected from the focus group and that
   cover several questions related to student's perceptions of fake news
   and online disinformation. The sample was composed of eight students who
   were attending the 2nd year of a bachelor's degree in Media and
   Communication in 2018/2019. The results emphasize that students are
   familiar with fake news and with what seems to motivate people to create
   and disseminate them. They are also aware of some specific
   characteristics of this type of news and can identify websites that
   usually publish false stories. Participants reveal that most of the
   manipulated news they have found are released on social media and
   suggest that the news and information they trust most are those they can
   get from printed media. The results obtained advocate that students are
   aware of the negative impact of the phenomenon and that education is the
   best way to prevent the dissemination of fake news}},
