Month = {{JAN}},
Abstract = {{This text aims to take a picture of the current situation of
   verification in Europe by studying several European fact-checkers. With
   the outbreak of the coronavirus pandemic, it has also been studied how
   it has affected the work of verifiers. To do this, a content analysis of
   the information they publish is carried out, trying to find similarities
   between the initiatives and seeking to understand the nature and
   characteristics of the misinformation with which they work. In addition,
   interviews with professional verifiers and fact-checking specialists
   will allow us to understand their routines, methodologies, and business
   structures, trying again to establish convergences in the European
   scenario. An attempt will also be made to see how the disinformation
   crisis caused by the coronavirus has affected these media. In the end we
   find constant activity and similarities in the contents and
   methodologies. Social networks (58\% of content) and politics (68\% of
   pieces) as the main routes and themes for disinformation in Europe.
   Fact-checking as a feasible outlet for journalists, although it does not
   bring great benefits for companies. Finally, the coronavirus health
   crisis has led to an increase in the work of these initiatives (In most
   cases it has meant a double increase in published pieces).}},
