Pages = {{189-204}},
Month = {{APR}},
Abstract = {{High individual risk taking, whether in terms of life-style risks or
   others, has often been explained in terms of acceptance of risks or
   misperception of the possible negative outcome. This article challenges
   this view, and points to a kind of risks that does not seem to fit this
   explanation. These risks are referred to as risks from vulnerability.
   They are taken because there are no positive alternatives to them, and
   the choice is perceived as having an element of hope. A new framework is
   proposed in order to expand these explanatory factors within the risk
   perception research. This framework analyzes individual risk taking in
   terms of: poor outset conditions, lack of reasonable options, hope, and
   liability to disinformation.}},
